text:
del 2

inte ens feministerna bryr sig om oss. dom bryr sig enbart om den "stereo typa svensken" som blir våldtagen eller antastad. ni kanske minns när hon som blev gruppvåldtagen i ett trapphus utav flera personer som själv var missbrukare för något år sen. var fanns #metoo då? 
helt jävla knäpptyst! så därför så gillar jag inte dem flesta feminister, för dom delar upp folk i fack, annars hade jag förmodligen blivit feminist med tanke på vad jag har fått utstå när det kommer till män. 
jag har själv sålt mig för pengar, vilket är något jag ångrar oerhört mycket idag. och jag hoppas dom killar som betalade mig skäms! för det spelar ingen som helst roll om jag gick med på det. man utnyttjar inte en kvinna i en sådan sårbar sits. samma gäller sex utan betalning. du knullar inte på en sådan skör och trasig tjej för att sedan ignorera henne förutom när du är kåt då och vill ha sex igen. det hade varit okej om killar hade varit ärliga ifrån första början, och sagt att dem faktiskt inte ville ha något förhållande. istället för att ljuga mig rakt upp i ansiktet och säga det dom tror jag vill höra enbart för att få sig ett skjut! 
det är det mina vänner - som kallas för "fuckboys" och dem finns överallt i alla dess åldrar!

det är därför som jag håller mig till snälla och nördiga gamers. för att dem helt enkelt vet hur man ska behandla och respektera en kvinna. dem tänker inte bara på sex som alla dessa vältränade douchbags gör som lever på gymmet varje dag.

dessutom är jag ju själv en gamer så därav mitt stora intresse för just sådana killar. <3 
tänker avsluta denna långa text med några urklipp ifrån vad killar brukar skriva till mig på tinder. tänker dock inte outa dem. även om jag är bra sugen med tanke på hur vissa skriver till mig. här är som sagt några exempel på hur dem flesta killar beter sig idag! "men ge mig en chans nångång dååå" "jävlar villka lökar" "öppen för sex?" "vill du knulla för en flaska vin?" "vill du äta ben & jerrys och knulla? ordningen valfri." listan kan som sagt göras lång tyvär. dom ska iaf ha cred för att dem var ärliga.
name: Marie Spansk

text:
today is the 5 year anniversary of an extremely painful experience that completely changed the trajectory of my life. at the time, i felt like a fraud anyway, so it made some kind of warped sense to me that i shouldn't have happiness and that i couldn't achieve the goals i had set myself. today, as i reminisce, i am so #grateful. for where i am now, for who i am, for everything i lost (because it wasn't mine to keep), for everything i've gained in the process - & for the fact that i now believe in myself and my own value. i am no longer the same person. and for that i am so #grateful.

speaking about your experiences and emotions will assist you in processing events that have occurred in your life.

if you feel your story may be too much for someone else to carry, verbalise it without an audience. just speak aloud everything has happened and finish when you reach where you are today. 
this process can help you to see your progress and what events you need to work on.

you are not alone in this, you have been there all along to witness your journey.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
jak powinna wyglądać skrzywdzona osoba, żebyś jej uwierzył?
może mieć umorzone dochodzenie w sprawie gróźb, które otrzymała w prywatnej wiadomości na facebooku od mężczyzny z jej środowiska zawodowego?

po moim poście o zgłoszeniu gróźb na policji napisało do mnie wiele kobiet. opowiadały o swoich doświadczeniach ze zgłaszaniem gróźb, stalkingu i przemocy na policji. ich zgłoszenia niemal zawsze kończyły się umorzeniem. czuły się totalnie zignorowane. okazywało się, że grożenie, szantażowanie, poniżanie i cyberprzemoc „nie zawiera znamion czynu zabronionego”. dla prawniczek i prawników, z którymi konsultowałam się przed zgłoszeniem, sprawa była oczywista: to groźby karalne. dla znajomych też. dla policjantki, u której złożyłam zeznanie, także. ale dla organów prawnych już nie. w miejscu „uzasadnienie” pusto. nie ma uzasadnienia dla bezkarności przemocy.

system prawny stoi po stronie sprawców. od lat agresywni faceci mogą bezkarnie znęcać się nad kobietami. ale tym razem uznany wydawca nie pozostał całkowicie bezkarny. publicznie opisałam jego seksistowskie komentarze wobec pisarek w poście na facebooku, zgłosiłam groźby, które po tym poście mi wysłał, musiał udać się na policję i złożyć czterogodzinne zeznania. sprawa nie pozostała między straszącym i straszoną. już przez samo to poniósł większe konsekwencje niż olbrzymia większość sprawców przemocy – mimo umorzenia dochodzenia. i dokładnie dlatego czuł się niesprawiedliwie potraktowany, a ludzie ze środowiska mu współczuli – nie dlatego, że tego nie dokonał: sprawa jest wyjątkowo oczywista, są skriny i dowody. dlatego, że zwykle takie zachowania pozostają bezkarne lub wręcz hołubione w gawędach o nieposkromionych poetach. a kobiety cierpią w ciszy. „poczekajmy na decyzję sądu”. „to sprawa dla prokuratora, nie dla mediów”. „dlaczego nie zgłosiłaś tego na policji?”. dlatego.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
미투 1년. 서지현 검사께서 홍성수 <말이 칼이 될 때>를 읽고 계신다고 합니다. 선생님과 이 책을 만들 때부터 헤아려봐도 혐오와 증오로 인한 사건들이 한국에선 수없이 벌어졌어요. 다 헤아리기 힘들 정도로. 그 중에서도 서지현 검사의 사건은 오래 듣고 있기도 힘들었는데(내가 이런데 본인은 어땠을까), 이분이 내가 만든 책을 읽고 계시다니. 고맙고 고마운 마음입니다. 아주아주 작으나마 진심으로 연대한다는 마음이 전해졌으면 하고요. .
. -요새 어떤 책을 읽고 있나요. =혐오 관련 책을 읽어요. (웃음) 최근엔 홍성수 교수의 <말이 칼이 될 때>를 읽었어요. 홍 교수도 굉장히 많은 욕을 먹고 있더라고요. 혐오를 반대한다는 데 왜 욕을 먹어야 하는지 이해를 못하겠어요. 여성을 동등하게 대해달라는데 왜 욕을 먹어야 하는지. . .
. -혐오를 공부하는 게 검찰에 복귀해서도 도움이 되겠네요. =그렇죠. 책을 읽었기 때문에 지금도 이렇게 이야기할 수 있는 거예요. (웃음) . .
. -전자우편 주소가 인상적이었어요. (서 검사의 전자우편 주소는 ‘행복’과 ‘웃음’이라는 뜻의 영어 단어가 포함돼 있다.) =17~18년 전 전자우편이라는 걸 처음 만들면서 가진 아이디예요. 연수원 시절 때 별명이 ‘해피 걸’(happy girl)이었어요. 잔걱정 없고 항상 행복하고 감사해하며 살아왔거든요. 인생의 방향이 이렇게 틀어지리라곤 생각을 못했죠. .
.
.

text:
americans are awake. that’s what my boyfriend said yesterday afternoon when he started getting 3 hate msg-s per minute. 
there is a whole outrage in the usa art circles right now, because of boris’s art. by presuming, projecting, jumping to conclusions, and overall superficiality, idea that he is a racist has been formed and spread with the light speed of the instagram. 
his art is provocative, he uses humor and racist symbols to expose the hypocrisy. 
looking at it superficially, you would read it as racist without doubt. that’s where instagram, a perfect tool for idiotizing the people, comes in handy. to look at everything for one second and form the opinion based on that one second. on the other hand, if you would dive in deeper, you would see how he manipulates observers into a complicated emotional game, bringing out the subconscious ideas, fears and other emotions that get buried under the weight of a taboo. in this case racism and immigration.
we could argue weather it’s good or bad, weather it works or not, but i’m not here to defend his art.

what i want to talk about is political correctness and it’s evolution from correctional tool for malign social behavior, into a strong censorship tool, bordering fascism. 
i never liked political correctness, but now i’m scared shitless of it. it went out of control. now i’m even starting to think it is a construct created by right wing in us, to destroy the left from the inside. because it’s doing such good job of just that. creating huge gaps between people who are fighting on the same side.
another thing i find fascinating is the, righteousness, confidence and moral supremacy of the people attacking on social media, even when they are utterly uninformed. i have seen this happening with other cases, with #metoo movement especially, and was waiting to see this creep into other stuff. #borishoppek #politicalcorrectness #politicalcorrectnessgonemad #racism #immigration

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

@arimelber @maddowshow @seanhannity i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagate™ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
vad @elaineeksvard skriver👆och vad jag nu säger. jag är ju redan på g att bli åtalad för grovt förtal, för att jag vägrade hålla tyst längre. så håll i hatten. häxan brinner.
det som kommit fram i och med #metoo är skrap på ytan. ni skulle bara veta. era svenska favvo-skådisar, den där manlige geni-regissören som hyllas internationellt och pratar om feminism i intervjuer, artisten som pratar varmt om antirasism, f.d politikern som gjort karriär på att verka för jämställdhet.. alla män. och tyvärr också våldtäktsmän, övergreppare, sexuella trakasserier, grooming av småtjejer... glömde jag nämna en av våra mest folkkära komiker som sitter på hotellrum på sina turnéer och groomar tonårstjejer som likear på hans insta? ni skulle bara veta en bråkdel av allt jag vet. allt jag sett bevis på. ...
men nu är det andras tur att börja prata. för jag är långt ifrån enda som vet, har bevis. jag är inte hela sveriges outnings-jourtjänst. nu är det andras tur (och då framförallt ni med makt, pengar, hyfsat lite att förlora) att börja berätta vad ni vet. men som nån sa till mig häromdan: ”jag kan ju inte berätta vad jag vet om xxx, då kommer ju bolaget xxx gå i konkurs”... är det #nomorefuckstogive bara om nån annan gör det, i praktiken? hur ska vi ha det, kära kollegor och medmänniskor? ni väljer. vilka ska vi skydda mest? ni väljer.

text:
@ylex @nyt.fi @nytimes bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
photo: construction of the trans-siberian railway⠀
⠀
the trans-siberian railway⠀
the project’s financial and technical challenges were immense, and construction proved to be a nightmare. the harsh siberian climate hampered progress all along. large rivers had to be bridged, and large extensions of land were either waterlogged or unyielding permafrost. the lack of labor in remote places meant that soldiers, conscripts and gulag prisoners had to be brought in. up to 90,000 men were employed in the construction.⠀
⠀
read further at https://buff.ly/2bot3ks on the history the trans-siberian railway that lily used to travel in russia, across eight time zones, in the blog: the trans-siberian railway⠀
⠀
 #historicalfiction #historicalromance #womenfiction #metoo #weshallseetheskysparkling⠀
#susanaaikin #transsiberian #railway #railroad #adventuretravel

text:
bernardo bertolucci (1941-2018)
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
'파리에서의 마지막 탱고', '마지막 황제' 등으로 명성을 떨친 이탈리아의 베르나르도 베르톨루치 감독이 77세의 일기로 타계했다.
베르톨루치 감독은 그간 허리 디스크 등으로 여러 차례 수술을 받은 후 휠체어 생활을 해오고 있었다. 그와 각별한 친분을 나누었던 이탈리아의 명배우 로베르토 베니니는 이탈리아 영화의 '마지막 황제'가 우리 곁을 떠났다며 그의 죽음을 애통해 했다.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
1941년 이탈리아 북부 파르마에서 시인 이틸리오 베르톨루치의 아들로 태어난 그는 부친의 영향으로 유년 시절부터 윤택한 문화적 토양에서 성장했다. 아버지의 친구였던 피에르 파올로 파졸리니 감독의 조감독으로 영화계에 입문, 22살이던 1962년에 '냉혹한 학살자'로 데뷔하면서 영화계의 주목을 받기 시작했다. 이후 그는 인간이 겪게 되는 분열과 갈등에 시각을 맞추며 '1900년' '혁명전야' '스틸링 뷰티' 등의 명작들을 만들어낸다.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
베르톨루치 감독은 1987년 작품인 '마지막 황제'로 감독상을 포함해 아카데미 9개 부문을 휩쓸었다. 2007년에는 그간의 공적을 인정받아 베니스영화제 특별상인 명예 황금사자상을 받은 바 있다.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

text:
when is the last time you thanked yourself, your entire being, for all of the ways you’ve been able to navigate life up until this point? 
it’s easy to get lost in frustrations about things we’re struggling with and circumstances we wish were different. but for thirty seconds, a few breaths in and out, can you feel what it’s like to just sink into yourself with a full heart and say “i’m still here.” we are incredible and resilient beings. complicated and so damn worthy. 
our systems by nature do whatever they can to help us persevere through traumatic events to keep us alive. the tricky part is that sometimes we hang on to those survival skills far beyond when we need them; what we once used to get though something difficult can shift into our standard mode of operation, putting our systems in overdrive (or park). we can find ourselves hanging on to coping skills that were useful and often brilliant when we were in the thick of it, but that now hold us back from where we’re trying to go. •what are you hanging on to that you no longer need? •what can you show gratitude toward and say farewell to? •how can you honor what you’ve learned and make space for healing and growth?

#brave #selflove | quote adapted from @eboneedavis

text:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
@thejimmydoreshow @bbcnews @nbcnews @anakasparianofficial @turunsanomat wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
“i was lucky, i was only raped by three men.” -rohingya survivor.

the burmese military systematically uses rape as an instrument of terror against its ethnic populations. 
thousands of testimonies and physical injuries bare witness to the assaults launched by the junta. 
the un report describes the attacks. the burmese army would enter villages late at night, “the operations were designed to instil immediate terror, with people woken by intense rapid weapon fire, explosions or the shouts and screams of villagers. structures were set ablaze (and locked with people still inside), and tatmadaw soldiers fired their guns indiscriminately into houses and fields, and at villagers.” men unable to get away were often tortured, or forced to become porters for the army, many of which were killed after a few months. women and girls were separated, gang-raped in front of one another by dozens of soldiers for hours at a time, and then killed or bodies severely mutilated. 
i have had the privilege to interview and work with the ethnic women in the contested states of burma. hear their horrific recounts. but what breaks my heart, is how normalized this has become. they are able to talk of the rape they’ve witnessed or experienced in such a casual way due to the sheer numbers of women they know who have experienced the trauma. rape has become almost as expected as rain during the monsoon season. 
the burmese military carries out these hellacious crimes against humanity with total impunity, and as the united nations reports, “it consistently fails to attribute responsibility, thereby reinforcing its message to troops that they will face no consequences.” i beg for the international community: such as individual nation-states, the united nations and the international criminal court to come forward and hold accountable those responsible for the systematic use of rape, ethnic cleansing, and genocide in the contested states of burma.

report: https://www.ohchr.org/documents/hrbodies/hrcouncil/ffm-myanmar/a_hrc_39_64.pdf (note:to protect the identity of the women i interviewed and those i work with, these are not personal photos but those already cleared and published.)

text:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text_retweet:
@regran_ed from @warif_ng -  december 07 | day 13

feeling safe again after a sexual assault can be one of the most challenging aspects of healing, and is often a struggle for survivors. facilities for care and support are necessary to help survivors through this time.

the warif centre is a safe haven where survivors are helped in a step by step approach through the initial traumatic phase of their experience and the necessary follow-up visits.  available to all, we provide medical care, psycho social counselling, legal services  and access to shelters totally free of charge.

share our stories, repost, tag someone and join us in the #orangetheworldwithwarif campaign as we participate in the #16daysofactivism against gender based violence.

warif centre: 6, turton street, off thorburn avenue, yaba, lagos.
warif confidential helpline: 08092100009

text:
@cnn @nyt.fi @huffpost wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

jon sharman

text:
por lucía, desde el piso, hacia el cielo

lucía pérez nunca había estado en buenos aires. poco antes de ser violada y asesinada en octubre de 2016, en mar del plata, su mamá, marta montero, le había prometido que iban a viajar a conocer la ciudad. pero la violencia machista la mató cuando apenas tenía 16 años. y la justicia patriarcal la volvió a matar hace apenas una semana. esta tarde, mientras en manada feminista nos tirábamos al piso frente al obelisco para recordarla, su mamá veía a lucía en buenos aires, en ese viaje que le prometió y que le arrebataron de un cachetazo. lucía estuvo hoy en cada foto, en cada grito, en cada canto, en cada mirada que, desde el piso, la buscaba en el cielo. ese mismo cielo que marta evocó una y otra vez para referirse a lucía. ese mismo cielo reflejado en nuestros rostros llenos de gibré y lágrimas.

lloramos por lucía, lloramos por natalia melman, por diana sacayán, por melina romero, por micaela garcía… y por tantas otras. porque la violencia machista nos mata a todas. porque lucía somos todas.

no podrán disciplinarnos. frente a la justicia patriarcal, memoria feminista.

text:
"in times of trauma, like a sexual assault, you don’t think clearly and you don’t file memories correctly all the time. there are things i can't remember -- and things i'll never forget"
.

meet trauma informed yoga teacher @yoginijulie sharing her #yogasavedmylife story with us. these are her words 💚
.
. "i remember what i was wearing -- a baggy sweatshirt, and jeans. it was a weeknight, and we were going to watch a movie. as i relaxed with my feet up on my friend's couch, he brought me a tall, fizzy, orange-flavored drink. then it’s all a blank -- until i woke up later on his bed. he was on top of me. i registered what was happening, but paralyzed and terrified, i passed out again
.
i drove back to my apartment later, called my parents, and moved home. the police wouldn't even take my story. i talked to my therapist, and that was helpful, but i still struggled with anxiety attacks and bouts of severe depression. but then i found what would change me forever -- yoga
.
it started as simple exercises, then become a daily practice of meditation, mindfulness, spirituality, and reconnecting with my body.i hated my body -- i wanted to escape it, to hide away and live in my head
.

trauma-sensitive yoga, however, teaches how to be gentle with yourself, to be in the moment, and find that comfort and healing once again. it was absolutely life-changing for me. i even reached a point where i was able to forgive my attacker, inside myself, and stop the cycle of hate. i studied tsy as much as i could, and became a certified teacher. now i am thrilled to be able to help and guide other women on their own path to healing. i truly feel this is my purpose in life
.

it happened to me too, like it happens to too many others. but nobody took anything away from me. i’m still whole and i’m complete. and now, with yoga as a tool and a lifestyle, i'm stronger than ever before 🙏 julie
.
.

text: did you know that out of the 394 members of the british stunt register only 62 of them are women.  so why are there so few women in the stunt industry? many are pointing to the practice of “wigging” – which is when male stunt actors play female characters. deven macnair, a los angeles-based stuntwoman, is believed to be behind the first ever legal challenge against this practice. but this seems to be one of many issues within the stunt industry, macnair says women contact her regularly sharing allegations about tv and film productions, ranging from sexual harassment to workplace discrimination, yet they won’t go public. “keep in mind that these are the strongest, most badass women in america and they are silent”. if very powerful women in hollywood haven’t felt empowered enough to come forward about sexual misconduct until relatively recently, then it’s perhaps unsurprising that women behind the camera are yet to have their metoo moment, staying silent out of self-preservation. this needs to change. #metoomovement#metoo#stuntwomen#stuntwomenunited#actionwomen#adventure#badasswomen#genderequality#womenempowerment

"you don't realise how much you have neglected yourself until you make yourself a priority again"

learning to love yourself after abuse, is one of the first steps to recovery. put yourself first and when you start doing the things you stopped, you will start to heal.

text:
feature friday
afda film hits home

afda port elizabeth honours graduation film, isikhalo: the outcry, directed by loren buchner and sisanda dyantyi, is gaining a great deal of traction for highlighting a pertinent issue facing women in sa – spousal rape.

the film introduces ciki, a young women who grew up in a small hamburg village who marries a suburban high school teacher. after moving to ntselamanzi township with her bantu, she discovers her husband is not the man she imagined him to be. supported by her fellow stokvel friends, ciki finally stands up to his archaic interpretation of cultural standards, and so begins a journey of courageous self-discovery “the day that i knew when “isikhalo” was going to make an impact, was when the numetro projectionist, a middle-aged male, came out of the projecting room to congratulate and hug the crew after the test screening of the film before the afda graduation festival.” says mark wilby, afda pe head of postgraduate studies.

if you have as yet not had the opportunity to watch the film, watch it here: https://afda.co.za/film/733/isikhalo:%20the%20outcry/

text: dear men- don’t be this guy. honestly, don’t approach women like this. you want to talk to someone or get to know someone? you should probably at the very least look at their page and see what they stand for and what their interests are and if they’re in a relationship. instead y’all just play the same basic card- “let me call her pretty so that she’ll talk to me”. it’s tired and gross. to me anyway. #dontcallmepretty @dontcallmepretty_ #metoo #womenempowerment #menpleaselearnhowtotalktowomen if you come at me in my messages like this i’m going to use you as an example. also, women- don’t do this to guys either. don’t randomly message men saying what’s up sexy, that’s not okay either. anyway. the bottom line is- if you’re all trying to find someone through instagram- maybe you should actually look at who you’re #instastalking instead of just focusing on the face. 🤷🏻‍♀️🤦🏻‍♀️🙄 #overit

text:
yesterday was national day of remembrance on violence against women. 
it's also happens to be the day i was re-victimized, by questions like, "well was there alcohol involved?" like that is even a relevant factor. 
i didn't acknowledge it yesterday, because like so many victims of violence, i was ashamed. 
but i'm over it. 
part of being so open about sharing my journey, the good, the bad and the super ugly, is  that i know there are other women out there, reading my posts and seeing themselves in them. 
i know this because every once in a while, someone reaches out and says "thank you for helping me know i am not alone." and it fills my heart. 
my journey is about healing. healing my body, my mind, and my spirit. 
if you are a survivor of violence, i want you to know this; 🔹you are not alone 🔹it is not your fault. ever. in no way shape or form is what happened to you your fault. period. 🔹 you will come out the other side of this. it's going to be an ugly ride, but you are a survivor. 🔹 you are loved. and in those moments you don't feel it, know that as someone who understands, i love you.

text:
thank you, thank you, thank you @sipinsoma @danielleperrotta for allowing me to tell the beginning of my journey of #survivorship, which is an ongoing journey to this day. please listen to my @sipinsoma podcast interview that just dropped yesterday via my linktree link in bio 👆🏽where you can also purchase my novella the survivors club for $6 ($5 goes to charity). the holidays can be triggering and there’s a ton of family time that can be difficult for survivors of child abuse. take time out for yourself. breath, meditate, and remind yourself that you can create the holiday experience that you want in little ways—whether it is by decorating your house they way you wanted it to look as a  child but couldn’t (that’s me! ✋🏽) or if you want to play certain music, make special food, create a new tradition with your kids, whatever! carve out a way to make it yours and be in the moment about it. i am thankful for my community of support and for amazing people like @danielleperrotta who truly let me shine during this interview 😘
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
kanye west speaks on sexual assault in his newly leaked collaboration with xxxtentacion titled, “one minute” - blogged by: @carmen.roxanna
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
kanye west caused more controversy on wednesday, after a new collaboration with the late #xxxtentacion was leaked prior to the release of xxx’s posthumous album “skins.” in the song, kanye makes reference to false rape allegations...and social media is on the fence about it.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
towards the end of west’s verse on the song, he says, “she wanna give you the cookie, you famous-amous. she gave you the pu**y, but you ain’t pay for the anus.
now your name is tainted, by the claims they paintin'. the defendant is guilty, no one blames the plaintiff.
gotta say it in layman’s terms, while you wait on arraignments;
cause if the jury say you did it, the payment is heinous.”
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
his verse suggests the potential damage to a man’s reputation that could come from false accusations of rape, which is part of the common pushback the discussion of sexual violence against women brings on, a topic that the #metoo movement has made extremely relevant this past year.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
some fans have theorized that kanye’s lyrics are a declaration of xxxtentacion’s innocence, but sources say kanye “is not defending xxx or anyone in particular,” and in actuality, the details surrounding the case x was facing don’t even correlate to the lyrics kanye spit. xxx, whose real name is jahseh onfroy, was in a legal battle involving physical violence... he was never charged with rape.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
kanye has been an ongoing supporter of the late florida rapper, ....…to read the rest log on to balleralert.com (clickable link on profile)

text:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

tweet_full:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significan notly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text: see what people are saying about candy apple butterscotch, #newauthor rebecca macceile’s debut publication. “this is an impactful read if you have ever experienced any sort of abuse. i appreciate the author’s candor and willingness to write with such openness. she takes responsibility for herself as much as she describes the lasting effects of trauma.” “it is worth the read. it’s about a woman empowered and, my god, that is a wonderful thing indeed.” “the author gets to the point while still painting a very clear and definite picture for the readers and i love that. the accounts of the trauma are laid out in such a way that you know what’s happening and are able to imagine it but you aren’t bombarded with intense graphic imagery, which i appreciate as a survivor myself. would definitely recommend!” “this amazingly written gem takes you inside the author’s world and keeps you there, making you feel like a discreet “bug on the wall.” i could not put it down.” “i wish everyone would write a memoir. it would be so much easier to understand people. i haven’t been through anything as violent or traumatic, but i think this story is relatable in a lot of ways. it just makes me see a lot of things differently in every day life. it’s a big eye opener.” #onsalenow at the #linkinbio. #kindle and #paperback versions available! also for members of #amazonprime, candy apple butterscotch is available in the #kindlelendinglibrary as well as through #kindleunlimitedbooks! that’s right you can read for #free. #nonfictionbooks #memoir #metoo #ptsdsurvivor #kindlestoryteller2018  #kindledirectpublishing #onsalenow #paperback #kindlelendinglibrary #bookrecommendations #indieauthor #authorsofinstagram #amazon #readforfreekll

text:
@radiohelsinki @katyturnbc @huffpostitalia @foxnews in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

and after years of building courage as a woc in a white man’s world (hollywood) she told her story. in a self centering “apology” lena admits she used her power to publicly accuse aurora of lying, when *lena* was actually lying. .
.
she not only silenced another woman, but a woc, + the voices of woc have been endlessly violently marginalized + silenced by white women.
.
we are not outraged enough at this violence against perrineau. .
.
this is not a minor slip. this is a major moment to understand why white feminism is so violent + ww are not trusted. please pay attention. follow biwoc, stay silent + respectful in their spaces, google what you don’t understand, pay a biwoc to help you unpack your privilege, disrupt the dinner table. there is no dismantling patriarchy without dismantling racism. follow @gutsygirlart @rachel.cargle @laylafsaad @shishi.rose @kimcrayton1 @leesareneehall @adriennemareebrown @mckensiemack + let them lead you to more woc. do the work. if i, if you, say something wrong, + i will + we will, allow yourself to be taught. there is a lifetime of unlearning to do. the fact that lena limited the comments on her problematic last post proves an unwillingness to learn. don’t be fragile, be strong, be

text:
@huffposttaste @foxnews @nytimes - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
my sincerest thank you to everyone that watched, supported & shared. i have a love for a number of things but scripting, directing and film production are absolutely at the top of that list! to aisha and the other survivors you will hear as the series continues i thank you for trusting me with your stories! i received word last night that while a family was watching your story a young girl came forward about something that had secretly transpired in her life! this matter is so much bigger than us and it is my desire that it will continue to liberate the hearts that are heavy & bound! this is a conversation that can no longer wait. it's definitely a hard one but somebody has to have it! lastly, congratulations to all those who have begun this journey! this is freedom!

text:
after highly successful roundtable events in nyc in april, june and november, the fourth in the ongoing series ‘the real-world implications of #metoo – transforming the legal ecosystem,’ hosted by @fiscalnote, her justice and @thomsonreuters, at the denver offices of dentons us llp on december 4th, gave lawyers a forum in which to engage in frank, off-the-record conversation about the role they can play in the context of the #metoo movement. 
l-r joel hamel, susan banks and britton nohe-braun (dentons us llp, denver), dave curran, senior vice president & chief business officer at fiscalnote, jessica brown, partner at gibson, dunn & crutcher llp and joe kennedy, her justice volunteer and committed advocate for women’s rights.
.
.
.
#empowerwomen #womensrights #metoo #justice

text:
during the month of november, our advocates responded to 287 sexual assault crisis calls. that breaks down to almost 10 sexual assaults per day. we must do more to stop sexual violence.

help is available for victims of sexual violence. our advocates can explain the exam process, the saki project, what it might look like to report to law enforcement, how to get a protection order, and much more. you do not have to do this alone. 
1.800.770.1650 or text 'iowahelp' to 201-21.

text:
on thursday’s episode of "the michael knowles show," michael discussed the "hypocrisy" of kamala harris, "#metoo hero." "so, kamala harris, senator from california, former attorney general of california, she has been an early lead [for presidential nomination]. i’ve said that she’s probably the scariest person right now, scariest in that we don’t know much about her. she’s clearly pretty intelligent. she checks off the intersectional boxes of the left," he said. "just today, just out today, there’s a negative news story about her." knowles explained how larry wallace, a former senior advisor to harris while she served as ag, settled a $400,000 lawsuit for gender discrimination and harassment during harris’ transition from the california attorney general’s office to the senate. "that’s my tax money, anyone else who’s listening in california, that’s your tax money paying that out," he said. "and where it gets pretty dicey for her is that they asked kamala harris what about this major lawsuit almost half a million dollars for one of your senior advisors sexually harassing some woman, and harris’s office said they had no awareness of it. they had no idea what was going on." "this is not believable," he stressed. "this is not believable at all. this guy has worked with her in all of her major jobs, and this lawsuit occurred on her watch. so, either she’s lying, which obviously she is, or she’s totally incompetent. the office is totally incompetent if they’ve never heard of this. but it’s just not possible." knowles discussed how harris’ successor to california ag would have been the one who settled the suit, adding even more doubt to the story that the democrat lawmaker knew nothing about it. and to make matters worse, the alleged victim is forbidden to go to the media with her story.
this, said knowles, is the highest form of hypocrisy: "kamala harris positioned herself as the champion of the #metoo movement. kamala harris was there going after brett kavanaugh during all of those hearings. she believes christine blasey ford. she opposes brett kavanaugh. all but painted brett kavanaugh to be some gang rapist. and we need the truth to be heard!"
-the daily wire

text:
if you think your voice doesn’t matter, that you can’t make an impact with your actions, guess again.

time’s up legal defense fund, a gofundme campaign that raises money for legal defense funds for victims of sexual assault and harassment in the workplace raised more than $22 million this year — the biggest fundraiser in the entire history of gofundme.

although this post celebrates a small but pivotal shift in the #metoomovement, this is a storm with ever changing winds and fierce conditions. and it doesn’t only apply to women, men are just now finding the courage to break their silence as well.

isn’t this an uncomfortable conversation to be having amid the selfies and product flat lays that i myself celebrate everyday? 
yes, but if i can’t use my platform to shine a light on real fucking issues when it counts, it blatantly kicks dirt on my right to freely post all my floaty poetry, playfulness and curated photographs that people before me fought so hard for.

while i’ve never had a personal story to add to the #metoo conversation, i’ve listened with my stomach in knots, as both friends and strangers have told me theirs over the last few years.

it’s easy to slouch into the shadows. walking tall is hard, and even though it might take all your strength just to put one foot in front of the other, you’re still moving forward. please know that you can still be brave even though your hands are shaking. you’re not alone.

text:
la violencia de género es aquella que sufrimos las mujeres por el mero hecho de serlo. 
a veces siento que es un concepto extraño, con el que muchas aún no estamos familiarizadas, pese a que representa una realidad que llevamos tatuada en la piel desde que nacemos. 
desde niñas nos acostumbramos a agachar la cabeza ante la desigualdad, a esforzarnos más para conseguir menos, a resistir aunque nuestro cuerpo arda por dentro. 
crecemos con la idea de que no estamos completas, que el error está en nosotras, que somos menos. 
pero sobre todo, crecemos en silencio, no vaya ser que nuestra voz moleste a alguien. 
pero ya va siendo hora de pegar un grito bien fuerte. todas juntas. un grito de resistencia que invada el mundo entero de sororidad, empatía y amor. 
mujeres, es hora de que se nos escuche. .

16 días de activismo contra la violencia de género de @unwomen .

#hearmetoo #16days #orangetheworld #escuchametambién #violenciadegenero #mujer #sororidad #resistencia #igualdad #yotambien #metoo #niunamenos #unwomen #unwomenasia

text:
when i saw this...it took me forever to find the one right side up...but as soon as i did...they all were facing up...now when i look at them it's a mix...some are up...some are down. i think it's a beautiful analogy for life....there is always a different perspective...a different way to look at things...the minute we close ourselves off to it...is the day we limit ourselves and our world.
regardless of your take on the🎵 baby it''s cold outside🎵ban...
it's like i can see both sides...my whole life i've loved that song...for real. but now with what's happening in todays world...you read it and just can see how the lyrics could be teaching our boys n girls not so great of a
 message.  if a girl does say no to you...umm multiple times... it was written in 1944...just different times. i'll still enjoy the song...nostalgia growing up if anything...but i'm not so closed off that i will be  throwing a fit if it's not on the 
radio anymore. 
it's still available on youtube, spotify, pandora etc 
it's like this picture....once you see it...someone could ask you 10 times how are the plates facing? down...down...do..ohhh upp..wait how can that be?
it all gets flipped and you start wondering how did we see it the other way so clearly.....but the people who don't care to see both sides..the ones that won't acknowledge there might be an other side that holds merit...
the second we start being afraid to speak up about what could be wrong,say what hurts us..scares..us...gasp! offends us....is the day we ....
ohhh wait we r already there....there was more outrage on a 1944 christmas song than children being locked up in cages....separated from their parents or the fact women were coming forward saying "this happened to me." #metoo
maybe before jumping to the side you think is so clear....we should just try...try...try
 to see it through someones
 else's life... because ironically if you had 2 people arguing upside down and right side up....they would both be right.

text:
. k n o w l e d g e 📚 under många år var skådespeleri och teater mitt absolut största intresse och det jag ville syssla med i framtiden. det är fortfarande ett stort intresse men det är länge sedan jag spelade själv. jag minns så väl min första teaterreplik på scen. jag var i tioårsåldern och vi spelade en pjäls om mobbning. det var gott om sånna på 70-talet 😝. vi var flera som spelade utsatta och jag spelade en skånsk kille som var mobbad för sin dialekt. (konstigt när jag tänker efter... det var bara pojkkaraktärer i pjäsen och bara flickor som spelade 🤔). hur som helst skulle jag då öva in min enda replik på skånska: "märkliga pågar som inte vill lära sig nåt nytt". jag tänkte inte så mycket på vad jag egentligen menade, mest på hur det lät. om det lät "verkligt". men den där repliken har liksom alltid följt med mig. många gånger i mitt liv har jag tänkt "märkliga pågar som inte vill lära sig nåt nytt" fast kanske inte just om pågar. för mig är ny kunskap och ny erfarenhet så enormt viktigt. ja gammal visdom 👓 är inte dålig den heller men att våga och vilja lära nytt är så oerhört betydelsefullt för att vi ska utvecklas och för att vårt samhälle ska utvecklas. tänk bara så många som lärt om i samband med #metoo. jag tänker att det också kan gå när det gäller den psykiska hälsan. att vi kan lära om och lära nytt. att vi lär oss stressreducera, ta hand om oss, ta hand om varandra 😍 våra anställda på arbetsplatser. att vi förstår vikten av att lyssna till elever och reducera kraven i skolan när de är i en akut sjukdomsfas. jag vill att vi lär oss mer om att inkludera människor med psykisk ohälsa i arbetslivet. så det är mitt tips på nyårslöfte: lära nytt om psykisk hälsa och lära oss #sättagränser ❤️
.
.
.
#gemenskap #välmående #måbra #hälsa #hälsosamlivsstil #nystart #livet #kunskap #tacksamhet #glädje #utbildning #nukörvi #relationer #framåt #tillsammans #utmaning #motnyamål #tacksam #mittliv  #livsstil #livskvalitet #kvalitetstid #njuter #njuta #egentid #komiform #friskluft #nyenergi

(konstigt när jag tänker efter... det var bara pojkkaraktärer i pjäsen och bara flickor som spelade 🤔). hur som helst skulle jag då öva in min enda replik på skånska: "märkliga pågar som inte vill lära sig nåt nytt". jag tänkte inte så mycket på vad jag egentligen menade, mest på hur det lät. om det lät "verkligt". men den där repliken har liksom alltid följt med mig. många gånger i mitt liv har jag tänkt "märkliga pågar som inte vill lära sig nåt nytt" fast kanske inte just om pågar. för mig är ny kunskap och ny erfarenhet så enormt viktigt. ja gammal visdom 👓 är inte dålig den heller men att våga och vilja lära nytt är så oerhö betydelsefullt för att vi ska utvecklas och för att vå samhälle ska utvecklas. tänk bara så många som lä om i samband med  jag tänker att det också kan gå när det gäller den psykiska hälsan. att vi kan lära om och lära nytt. att vi lär oss stressreducera, ta hand om oss, ta hand om varandra 😍 våra anställda på arbetsplatser. att vi förstår vikten av att lyssna till elever och reducera kraven i skolan när de är i en akut sjukdomsfas. jag vill att vi lär oss mer om att inkludera människor med psykisk ohälsa i arbetslivet. så det är mitt tips på nyårslöfte: lära nytt om psykisk hälsa och lära oss  ❤️

text:
#afdentskalender 
im heutigen türchen des afdentskalenders wird der adventskalender der berliner abgeordneten der afd "unterstützt". diese haben sich überlegt, ein adventskalender namens #jazuweißenmännern zu starten (kein witz, die meinen das wirlich ernst!). denn alte, weiße männer werden in letzter zeit anscheinend ganz schön diskriminiert. krass, habe ich gar nicht mitbekommen. gut, dass die afd auf solche probleme hinweist. deswegen poste auch ich heute einen mann, der die westliche lebensweise geprägt hat. also vielen dank an harvey weinstein und seine sexisten-freunde, dass dank euch die #metoo debatte so nötig war! 
und danke @afdentskalender für diese tollen aktionen :) #fckafd #fckrassism #wirsindmehr #gegendieafd

text: so today is one of those days. it’s not okay that i just took a million photos and i only think one of them is decent enough to show to the world. what kind of world is this that we live in where i’m not even comfortable in my own skin? im afraid to show people who i am without all the fakery that i know i use and that i am. today is a bad day, and all anyone is going to see is a photo. no i’m not stunning with or  without my makeup on or my hair perfected and i’m ashamed of this?! why?! people’s judgments and the worlds expectations of beauty and happiness are defeating me. who am i?! fuck knows. i am one of many lost people going through life. it’s not okay to feel uncomfortable with yourself and hate yourself, the only reason we feel like this is because society has made us this way..people have made us this way. i am sorry to everyone that’s feeling empty and lost because of the prejudices and naivety of others. young men and women strive to be an impossible kind of beauty. i’m forever wanting to be someone else and keep trying to get prettier, better, more what others want me to be, and i’m running out of energy to do that, i’m tired. this is who i really am #mentalhealthisinvisible #oneofthosedays #tryingtofightmyowndemons #itgetstough #thisiswhoireallyam #societyisfucked #wedothistoeachother #theworldcannotsurviveonnegativity #itisnotokay #metoo

text:
co zrobić, jeśli ktoś ci grozi, nęka, złośliwie niepokoi, obraża cię lub nawołuje do stosowania przemocy wobec kobiet w internecie?

to, co uznasz za słuszne i odpowiednie dla siebie w tym momencie - niezależnie od rad znajomych i nieznajomych, co powinnaś albo co zrobiliby na twoim miejscu. nie są na twoim miejscu. to ty decydujesz.

może potem będziesz szczęśliwa, że właśnie tak zdecydowałaś. może będziesz tego potem żałować. jak z wszystkimi innymi decyzjami. każda twoja reakcja, każde twoje odczucie jest ok. zły jest czyn sprawcy - i tylko on tu jest winny. molestowanie to próba wytrącenia ci kontroli nad własnym ciałem i życiem. to, co z tym zrobisz, to tylko twoja decyzja. nic nie powinno się wydarzyć wbrew twojej woli - sprawiedliwość nie może być powieleniem gestu odebrania kontroli.

a jeśli rozważasz ścieżkę prawną, to wskazówki: jakie są twoje prawa i jak się ich domagać. wszystko rozpisane w jednym miejscu, warto mieć pod ręką: http://www.hfhr.pl/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/jak-dzialac-gdy-spotkalam-sie-z-cyberprzemoca.pdf

jak powinna reagować skrzywdzona, żebyś jej uwierzył?
jak tylko chce.

text:
“it took me several days to build up the courage to do so, but eventually i did.i went to the police.
 3,894 days after the assault, 1,825 days since the end of the relationship, and 1,095 days since the memory returned to my conscious mind. in the united states the statue of limitations vary from state to state, crime to crime. where we were when the attack took place has a statute of 20 years. i got lucky. showing up to file my report was one of the most panic inducing things i’ve ever done. i showed up at the local police station and told the officer that i needed to report a nearly 11 year old rape. he was very kind, and encouraged me to stay, but he was honest and up front. after so much time had passed, with out any physical evidence it was really up to the prosecutor to determine if the case would move forward or not.” -r. macceile 2018 candy apple butterscotch: a memoir available now! #fourstars #memoir #metoo #ptsdsurvivor “it’s worth the read it’s about a #woman #empowered and my god that is a #wonderful thing indeed” #linkinbio #authorsofinstagram #independentpublishing #goodreads #newbookalert #readforfree now - dec 25th 100% of proceeds from my books go entirely toward my #holiday #charity #fundraiser benefiting the #afsp you can find more info on rebeccasbookshop.com

text:
this woman has rocked our world this past week. @milano_alyssa, you’re vital and appreciated beyond measure. please continue your work and know we’re all right behind you, willing servants in the massive conversation you so bravely kicked off with #metoo. endless thanks for your contribution to so many (including me). during her session at our leadership gathering, alyssa invited the local women from the neighboring islands to come join the conversation and she also invited all the female staff to participate. as a result of this, we met some incredibly brave women who have survived domestic violence, and then something extraordinary happened. the survivors told us how they needed to build a refuge, a shelter, a safe place women could come to and receive support and food. hearing this, our group from @businesschicks has committed to build this for them. there is so much bloody good in the world, and i feel so buoyed to continue to uncover it. 
#neckerisland #businesschicks #virginunite

text:
#fbf | 1954. a hotel suite in new york city. marilyn is married with the ex-player and has finished shooting the seven year itch. the sharpshooter is undercover as a hotel waiter and enters the room, deliberately dropping a newspaper, open to the photo of marilyn monroe on the subway grating, in front of the hotel suite. he smiles, looks around and then walks away. his design to end the marriage and break marilyn once more is going to work: the ex-player will be furious to see that his woman is once more the object of every horny man’s fantasy.

the ex-player opens the door, takes the newspaper, and begins to read it. his face changes. he is visibly perturbed. he hurts, and he’s going to make marilyn pay for it. he had asked her to only take serious roles, to be only his, but she didn’t listen. she’s now under his wrath, to be beaten like an animal with the very newspaper, and failing at another attempt of family happiness.

_______________

from the script of love is blonde:
joe: i was your husband. you've hurt me. i hope to god you never have babies. 
_______________

want to discover more about the sharpshooter and his motifs? support our #crowdfunding today: it’s running until december 14th, and we still have 15,000$ to reach our goal! please contribute any way you can via the #linkinbio: every dollar counts! if we don’t reach the entire goal, we won’t keep any donation, and marilyn’s truth will once again remain untold.

text:
how is voyeurism defined under the ipc?

section 354c of the ipc criminalises the act of voyeurism. it defines it as a man watching or capturing the image of a woman engaged in a private act in circumstances where she would usually not expect to be observed by the perpetrator or by any other person on the orders of the perpetrator or the distribution of an image so captured by the perpetrator.

what is the punishment for an act of voyeurism?

the punishment for committing this offence is simple or rigorous imprisonment of 1 to 3 years and a fine. repeated offenders are punished with simple or rigorous imprisonment of 3 to 7 years and a fine.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
a maioria dos homens subestima o nível de assédio sexual sofrido pelas mulheres, apontou uma pesquisa realizada pela ipsos moris pwrils of perception survey, que mede a diferença entre números reais e percepção da população em torno de um problema. o questionário foi respondido por residentes dos estados unidos e 12 países da europa.
a dinamarca foi o país que mais subestimou os números reais de assédio, que é de 80% entre mulheres a partir dos 15 anos. os homens dinamarqueses, entretanto, acreditam que a porcentagem é de apenas 31%.
em segundo lugar aparece a holanda, onde homens responderam que somente 38% das mulheres sofrem assédio quando o índice real aponta 73%. há quatro meses, um maestro da orquestra real holandesa foi demitido após acusações de abuso sexual.
os franceses ocupam a terceira posição de subestimação dos abusos sexuais, colocando que 41% das mulheres já sofreram com ele. de acordo com dados de 2012, 75% das francesas passaram por algum tipo de assédio. desde agosto, quem for denunciado pela prática pode pagar multa de até r$ 13 mil.
a percepção dos homens do reino unido — que apontaram 46% — sobre assédio foi a que mais se aproximou dos índices factuais. na ilha, 68% das mulheres foram vítimas de assédio em alguma etapa da vida.
uma pesquisa realizada este ano nos eua mostrou 81% das mulheres passaram por situações de assédio em algum momento da vida. para os americanos, este número não passa dos 44% mesmo após o escândalo envolvendo o produtor de hollywood, harvey weinstein, e campanhas como a #metoo.
a coordenadora do projeto everyday sexism, que recolhe experiências de assédio ou desigualdade de gêneros do dia-a-dia, afirmou que a pouca consciência entre os homens escancara a desvalidação das denúncias feitas por mulheres:
"temos um sério problema de credibilidade quanto aos relatos de abuso. tantas mulheres foram corajosas expondo assediadores e enfrentando inúmeras consequências por isso e, mesmo assim, as pessoas não acreditam nelas. precisamos que os homens lutem contra esse problema e sejam parte da solução."
fonte: o globo
#mulheres #violenciacontramulher #assedio #denuncie #nãovamosnoscalar
