a dinamarca foi o país que mais subestimou os números reais de assédio, que é de 80% entre mulheres a partir dos 15 anos. os homens dinamarqueses, entretanto, acreditam que a porcentagem é de apenas 31%.
em segundo lugar aparece a holanda, onde homens responderam que somente 38% das mulheres sofrem assédio quando o índice real aponta 73%. há quatro meses, um maestro da orquestra real holandesa foi demitido após acusações de abuso sexual.
os franceses ocupam a terceira posição de subestimação dos abusos sexuais, colocando que 41% das mulheres já sofreram com ele. de acordo com dados de 2012, 75% das francesas passaram por algum tipo de assédio. desde agosto, quem for denunciado pela prática pode pagar multa de até r$ 13 mil.
a percepção dos homens do reino unido — que apontaram 46% — sobre assédio foi a que mais se aproximou dos índices factuais. na ilha, 68% das mulheres foram vítimas de assédio em alguma etapa da vida.
uma pesquisa realizada este ano nos eua mostrou 81% das mulheres passaram por situações de assédio em algum momento da vida. para os americanos, este número não passa dos 44% mesmo após o escândalo envolvendo o produtor de hollywood, harvey weinstein, e campanhas como a #metoo.
a coordenadora do projeto everyday sexism, que recolhe experiências de assédio ou desigualdade de gêneros do dia-a-dia, afirmou que a pouca consciência entre os homens escancara a desvalidação das denúncias feitas por mulheres:
"temos um sério problema de credibilidade quanto aos relatos de abuso. tantas mulheres foram corajosas expondo assediadores e enfrentando inúmeras consequências por isso e, mesmo assim, as pessoas não acreditam nelas. precisamos que os homens lutem contra esse problema e sejam parte da solução."
fonte: o globo
#mulheres #violenciacontramulher #assedio #denuncie #nãovamosnoscalar

text:
@huffposttaste @foxnews @nytimes - bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ i was worried this would be a 250-page rant. i was worried it would make me even angrier, if that was possible. i shouldn’t have worried. i want everyone to read this book. the women who feel angry will feel so validated; the men who are wondering why we are so pissed will have some insights. and all of us will be given an overdue history lesson and a much needed correction on how we view women’s anger in this country.

she has done her research. she gives example after example of women’s rage leading directly to positive political change that benefits us all. women are not given the credit they deserve in our history books. we hear about white men’s anger as being a vital part of our nation’s founding, an admirable force for good. give me liberty or give me death! white men angrily broke free of imperialist control, then built a nation on slavery and the oppression of women, disenfranchising the majority of the population while holding literally all the power. women aren’t mentioned in the constitution, not once. we’ve had to fight for every right we enjoy today. and the fight is not over.

she talks in depth about the #metoo movement. she also addresses the need for white women to look at how women of color have been angry for a long time. while most of us got politically engaged after the 2016 election, women of color have been fighting against a white patriarchy all along. we cannot just come in and take over the resistance and act like we invented the idea. .

we also need to recognize that white women are still part of the problem. the majority of us voted for donald trump and for misogynist candidates like roy moore. black women overwhelmingly did not. we need to take a hard look at how white women are willing to take the benefits and the protection of the white patriarchal power structure at the expense of all oppressed people. this is a reckoning that is long overdue.

sometimes a book comes along that perfectly captures the political and societal moment as it’s morphing into a movement. traister has done an excellent job here. i highly recommend reading it; don’t be afraid of your anger.

⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ i was worried this would be a 250-page rant. i was worried it would make me even angrier, if that was possible. i shouldn’t have worried. i want everyone to read this book. the women who feel angry will feel so validated; the men who are wondering why we are so pissed will have some insights. and all of us will be given an overdue history lesson and a much needed correction on how we view women’s anger in this country.

she has done her research. she gives example after example of women’s rage leading directly to positive political change that benefits us all. women are not given the credit they deserve in our history books. we hear about white men’s anger as being a vital pa of our nation’s founding, an admirable force for good. give me libey or give me death! white men angrily broke free of imperialist control, then built a nation on slavery and the oppression of women, disenfranchising the majority of the population while holding literally all the power. women aren’t mentioned in the constitution, not once. we’ve had to fight for every right we enjoy today. and the fight is not over.

she talks in depth about the  movement. she also addresses the need for white women to look at how women of color have been angry for a long time. while most of us got politically engaged after the 2016 election, women of color have been fighting against a white patriarchy all along. we cannot just come in and take over the resistance and act like we invented the idea. .

we also need to recognize that white women are still pa of the problem. the majority of us voted for donald trump and for misogynist candidates like roy moore. black women overwhelmingly did not. we need to take a hard look at how white women are willing to take the benefits and the protection of the white patriarchal power structure at the expense of all oppressed people. this is a reckoning that is long overdue.

sometimes a book comes along that perfectly captures the political and societal moment as it’s morphing into a movement. traister has done an excellent job here. i highly recommend reading it; don’t be afraid of your anger.

text:
@thejimmydoreshow @bbcnews @nbcnews @anakasparianofficial @turunsanomat in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

it's time to shine your light so brightly! 
it's time to be unashamedly you!

text:
c’est un ciel bleu avec des fumigènes naturels.
et y’a pas de gilets jaunes, ni de crs, y’a pas de slogan, pas de foule, pas de cris, pas de coups, pas de feu, pas d’alarme, pas de pression, pas de vitesse, pas d’attente, pas de peur, pas d’orgueil, pas d’allure, passacaille. 
persuadée que la paix n’existe que dans le ciel, c’est pas pour rien que j’aime le faire descendre sur ton tel, vous êtes tous fous et c’est drôle à voir.
moi je suis folle de ciel.
